properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Unseasonably warm weather expected for the start of the Canada Day weekend. Saturday and Sunday are shaping up to be sunny with afternoon cloudy periods and isolated afternoon showers on Sunday. Temperatures will be about 5 degrees above seasonal normals for the period. This comes close to the Heat Warning criteria of at least 28 C for two or more consecutive days with an overnight low above 13 C. However, the amount of cloud cover, forest fire smoke and overnight cooling are still uncertain at this time and will play a major role in determining the temperatures. A Heat Warning may be issued later if conditions warrant. - Check the local news for health and safety updates. - Contact your local government to find out what services (such as air-conditioned buildings and public splash parks) are available in your area. - Environment and Climate Change Canada and Regional Medical Health officers expect an increase in health and safety risks from heat and are advising the public to take precautions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Wildfire smoke is creating locally reduced visibilities and producing poor air quality. ### Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors, and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. For more information please visit Alberta Health Services at www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/air.aspx. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 9:49 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, nickel to ping pong ball size hail and heavy rain. This severe thunderstorm is located east of Cardross and is moving to the east. Loonie-sized hail has been reported with this storm. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Fast-moving water across a road can sweep a vehicle away. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Intense lightning is likely with any thunderstorm that develops. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

Description: At 11:02 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a cluster of severe thunderstorms capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. There is a cluster of thunderstorms 20 km west of Buffalo Narrows, these storms are moving to the northeast at 50 km/h. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.
Expires: 2019-06-29T08:00:24-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-06-29T05:03:24-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1405840190.2019
Area: Buffalo Narrows and Peter Pond Lake
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of squalls with wind gusts up to 35 knots, frequent lightning and hail. Squalls near 35 knots are possible tonight if a thunderstorm moves across the lake. Heavy downpours suddenly reducing visibility to near zero are also possible. The threat of squalls is expected to end by Saturday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.
Expires: 2019-06-29T11:59:38-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-06-29T02:57:38-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.2512168942.2019
Area: Lake St. Clair

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 11:33 p.m. CST, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a dangerous thunderstorm capable of producing damaging wind gusts, up to nickel size hail and heavy rain. This line is located south of Coronach, near Scobey Montana, is heading to the northeast. ### Very strong wind gusts can damage buildings, down trees and blow large vehicles off the road. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.
